### Welcome to the T-Rex Runner project.
This is the final project for my Java course. You can download the [source](https://github.com/FracturedCodes/trexRunner/zipball/master) to compile and run it with `javac -g trexRunner.java && java trexRunner` (assuming you have [jre](java.com/download) and the [jdk](http://www.oracle.com/technetwork/java/javase/downloads/index.html).) Or you can follow this nifty tutorial and learn how to make your own!

### Resources you will need:
 - [java runtime env](java.com/download)
 - [java dev kit](http://www.oracle.com/technetwork/java/javase/downloads/index.html)
 - The pictures for the game (best download the [source](https://github.com/FracturedCodes/trexRunner/zipball/master))
 - A good text editor or IDE (I personally use [Sublime Text](https://www.sublimetext.com/))

### To begin:
 1. Good practice is to create a separate folder for your project, so go ahead and do that.
 2. Open up your text editor and create a new file named `trexRunner.java`.
 3. Import the necessary classes we will be using, in this case
    import javafx.application.Application;
	import javafx.stage.Stage;
	import javafx.scene.Scene;
	import javafx.scene.Group;
	import javafx.scene.canvas.Canvas;
	import javafx.scene.canvas.GraphicsContext;
	import javafx.scene.image.Image;
	import javafx.scene.paint.Color;
	import javafx.scene.text.Font;
	import javafx.scene.text.FontWeight;
	import javafx.animation.AnimationTimer;
	import javafx.event.EventHandler;
	import javafx.scene.input.KeyEvent;
4. Create the main class we will be working with. Since this is going to be a JavaFX application, the class should extend `javafx.application.Application`
    public class trexRunner extends Application {}
